<!--formatting and information for the text to provide hover effects-->
<section class="news pt-0 bg-white ">
  <div class="image-block-inner">
  <div class="card mt-md-5 my-5 shadow-lg p-3 mb-5 rounded", style="background-color: #301934"> 
    <div class="row ">
    <div class="text-center col-md-8 mx-auto text-white"> 
    <hr class="divider border border-5"/>
    <h2 class="mx-4 my-0 text-center">How Can You Help ? </h2>  <br> 
      <%= link_to 'Take Quiz', new_helpquiz_path, class:"btn btn-outline image-block-inner text-dark", style: "background-color: white" %> 
    <hr class="divider border border-5"/> 
    </div></div> 
    <ul class="row d-lg-flex list-unstyled image-block justify-content-center px-lg-0 mx-lg-0">
      <li class="col-lg-4 col-md-5 image-block full-width p-3">
        <div class="image-block-inner", style="background-color: white ">
          <a class="mh-100 text-dark" >
            <!--<img src="" alt="Picture1" class="img-responsive w-100"></a>-->
          <span class="hp-posts-cat">1.Recognizing Physical Warning Signs </span>
          <p class="mt-3"><a class="text-dark ">a. Black eyes <br>
          b. Busted lips <br>
          c. Red or purple marks on the neck <br>
          d. Sprained wrists <br>
          e. Bruises on the arms <br>
          </a></p>
          <!--  <p></p> -->
        </div> <!-- end of box outline -->
      </li>
      <li class="col-lg-4 col-md-5 image-block full-width p-3">
        <div class="image-block-inner", style="background-color: white">
          <a class="mh-100 text-dark">
            <!--<img src="" alt="Picture2" class="img-responsive w-100"></a> -->
          <span class="hp-posts-cat">2. Recognizing Emotional Signs</span>
          <p class="mt-3"><a class= "text-dark">
          a. Low self-esteem <br>
          b. Overly apologetic or meek <br>
          c. Fearful <br>
          d. Changes in sleeping or eating patterns <br>
          e. Depression Symptoms <br>
          f. Substance abuse <br>
          </a></p>
        </div> <!-- end of box outline -->
      </li>
      <li class="col-lg-4 col-md-5 image-block full-width p-3">
        <div class="image-block-inner", style="background-color: white">
          <a class="mh-110 text-dark">
            <!--<img src="" alt="Picture3" class="img-responsive w-100"></a> -->
          <span class="hp-posts-cat">3.Recognizing Behavioral Signs </span>
          <p class="mt-3"><a class= "text-dark" > 
          a. Becoming withdrawn or distant <br>
          b. Canceling appointments or meetings at the last minute <br>
          c. Being late often <br>
          d. Excessive privacy concerning their personal life <br>
          e. Isolating themselves from friends and family <br>
          </a></p>
        </div> <!-- end of box outline -->
      </li> 
      <li class="col-lg-4 col-md-5 image-block full-width p-3">
        <div class="image-block-inner", style="background-color: white ">
          <a class="mh-110 text-dark">
            <!--<img src="" alt="Picture3" class="img-responsive w-100"></a> -->
          <span class="hp-posts-cat">4. Believe The Victim </span>
          <p class="mt-3"><a class= "text-dark">  
          Consequently, victims often feel that no one would believe them if they told people about the violence. Believe the victim's story and say so. For a victim, finally having someone who knows the truth about their struggles can bring a sense of hope and relief.
          Offer the victim these assurances: <br>
          a. I believe you <br>
          b. This is not your fault <br>
          c. You don't deserve this.<br>
          </a></p>
        </div> <!-- end of box outline --> 
      <li class="col-lg-4 col-md-5 image-block full-width p-3">
        <div class="image-block-inner", style="background-color: white ">
          <a class="mh-110 text-dark">
            <!--<img src="" alt="Picture3" class="img-responsive w-100"></a> -->
          <span class="hp-posts-cat">5. Validate the Victim's Feelings</span>
          <p class="mt-3"><a class= "text-dark" > 
          It's not unusual for victims to express conflicting feelings about their partner and their situation. These feelings can range from: <br>
          a. Guilt and anger <br>
          b. Hope and despair <br>
          c. Love and fear <br> <br>
          If you want to help, it is important that you validate their feelings by letting them know that having these conflicting thoughts is normal. But it is also important that you confirm that violence is not okay, and it isn't normal to live in fear of being physically attacked. <br>
          </a></p>
        </div> <!-- end of box outline -->  
        </li>
        <li class="col-lg-4 col-md-5 image-block full-width p-3">
        <div class="image-block-inner", style="background-color: white ">
          <a class="mh-110 text-dark">
            <!--<img src="" alt="Picture3" class="img-responsive w-100"></a> -->
          <span class="hp-posts-cat">6. Understand The Reason Victims Stay </span>
          <p class="mt-3"><a class= "text-dark" > It can be hard to understand why someone you care about would seemingly choose to stay in an abusive or unhealthy relationship. Here are a few:<br>
          a. Fear of harm if they leave <br>
          b. They still love their partner and believe they will change<br>
          c. Their partner promised to change <br>
          d. A strong belief that marriage is "for better or worse" <br>
          e. Thinking the abuse is their fault<br>
          f. Staying for the children <br>
          </a></p>
        </div> <!-- end of box outline --> 
    </li>
    </ul>
    <%= link_to 'Back', href= home_DV_path,  class:"btn btn-outline image-block-inner text-dark", style: "background-color: white" %> 
  </div> 
</section> 
